4 ut erat etc.] ‘with his industry and vigour.’ There are at least three good ways of turning into Latin such a sentence as, ‘you with your usual kindness (will do this or the like)': (1) pro tua beneuolentia, (2) qua (or quanta) tu es beneuolentia, (3) ut es beneuolus.

modestissume, ‘implicitly,' ‘absolutely.’ Modestia, the opposite of licentia, is just the word for that obedience to discipline which Scipio made it his object to restore in the army: so 44. 1, 92. 2 modesto imperia
